SCHMALLENBERG VIRUS - EUROPE (06): (GERMANY) CLASSIFICATION, UPDATE
*******************************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 15 Dec 2011 [accessed 23 Dec 2011]
Source: Friedrich-Loeffler-Institut (FLI) Federal Research Institute
for Animal Health, Riems, Germany [in German, trans. Mod.AS, edited]
http://www.fli.bund.de/fileadmin/dam_uploads/tierseuchen/111221_Einstufung_Sicherheitsklasse_Schmallenberg-Virus.pdf


Classification in a safety class for the new _Orthobunyavirus_ in
Germany ("Schmallenberg virus")
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Rapporteurs: Dr Martin Beer, Dr Bernd Hoffmann

Introduction
------------
In November 2011, in the framework of its differential diagnostic
activities related to bluetongue virus (BTV), the Friedrich Loeffler
Institute demonstrated a new Orthobunyavirus (see ProMED-mail archive
no. 20111119.3404). The virus was provisionally named "Schmallenberg
Virus" (SBV).

The virus was detected in cattle showing short-term increase in body
temperature and significant milk yield decrease. The disease presented
since August 2011 in numerous farms in North Rhine-Westphalia
(particularly adjacent to the border with Holland). Positive real-time
RT-PCR results for SBV in dairy cows in this region have been obtained
in 11 samples from 5 farms.

The virus was grown in insect cells and later propagated in a hamster
cell line.

In the 1st animal experiment with 3 cows, viral propagation with a
short-lived viremia (days 2-5 post inoculation) was observed. One
animal showed elevated temperature (40.5 deg C/104.9 deg F) for one
day, the other animal moderate diarrhea.

All 3 genome segments (S, M, and L) of the SBV have been completely (S
and L) or partially (M) sequenced. All 3 segments show that the virus
is clearly identified as a representative of the genus
_Orthobunyavirus_. The highest homologies are obtained for the
orthobunyaviruses of the Simbu serogroup. However, since sufficient
sequences for comparison are available in the data bank only for the S
segment, further, more detailed classification could be based only on
the S segment. The S segment of SBV has been found to have the highest
homology (96 percent of the amino acid level) with the Shamonda virus.
The virus is therefore provisionally classified as "a Shamonda-like"
virus.

Simbu serogroup viruses are mostly found in Asia, Australia, and
Africa. According to literature, they are only very rarely associated
with clinical symptoms. An exception is their potential to induce
congenital defects, such as the ones caused by the Akabane virus.
Potential to cause congenital damage in ruminants may be attributed to
other members of the Simbu serogroup. Pathogenicity for humans, though
rare, has been reported (such as the Oropouche virus). Simbu serogroup
viruses are primarily transmitted by insect vectors (midges,
mosquitoes). The infection is not contagious. Viruses of the Simbu
serogroup have not been previously detected in Europe.

Suggested risk classification
-----------------------------
SBV should be considered for all laboratory work in the risk group 2.
For animal experimentation, it should be classified in risk group 3
[see commentary].

Background considerations
-------------------------
1. According to all data assembled thus far, SBV belongs to the Simbu
serogroup, which propagates primarily in ruminants and insect vectors.
In ruminants, the SBV caused subclinical or clinically mild infection.
Congenital damage, however, can not be excluded.

2. The close relationship (of the S segment) to Shamonda virus fits
into this picture and may indicate a similar behavior. The
relationship to Akabane virus and to the human pathogen representative
of this group (Oropouche virus) is significantly lower.

3. Most likely, the transmitter is an insect vector. This is supported
by the timing of occurrence of clinical signs and the genetic
classification.

4. There are no indications on human infections (such as, in laborers,
animal-handling personnel, other persons in the affected region).
However, this assumption is to be further studied (epidemiology,
serology of persons in the region, surveillance).

5. Animal studies deserve to be carried out under high security.
Therefore, analogous to the bluetongue virus where vector-free
conditions were required, level-3 safety requirements are, initially,
prescribed.

