[The German investigators and the FLI Institute are to be commended
for their swift and efficient handling of the novel Schmallenberg
virus (SBV, provisional name). The paper above includes some data
hitherto unpublished; this refers in particular to the results of the
preliminary infection trial in 3 cows, and the agent's apparent close
genetic relationship to the Shamonda virus (SHAV).

SHAV, an orthobunyavirus of the Simbu group, was initially isolated
from a bovine blood sample in 1965 in Nigeria [ref 1] and later
recovered from _Culicoides imicola_ collected in Nigeria between
November 1967 through December 1970 (ref 2). Its subsequent isolation
took place in Japan, where it was isolated from _Culicoides_ and blood
samples (2002) of sentinel cattle in Kagoshima and Miyazaki
Prefectures, in the southern part of Japan (ref 3). Interestingly,
genetic variation was found to be very low (about 3 percent nt
difference) between Nigerian and Japanese SHAV strains, although the
virus resurged in Japan far from Nigeria over 30 years later. So far,
no information on its pathogenicity and the host spectrum are
available. In view of SBV being the 1st Simbu-group virus detected in
Europe, its potential to cause congenital malformations in the highly
susceptible European ruminants may be regarded to be significant. As
the experience with Akabane virus shows, when endemic the virus will
rarely affect foeti since breeding animals become immune prior to
their 1st pregnancy.

Regarding risk classification, the authors refer, most likely, to the
classification prescribed in EU's legislation, "European Community -
Classification of infectious biological agents by risk group"
(Directive 2000/54EC of 18 Sep 2000, O.J. L 262, 17.10.2000, p.21).
The biological agents are classified according to their risk to
humans, as follows:
1. Group 1 biological agent: one that is unlikely to cause human
disease.
2. Group 2 biological agent: one that can cause human disease and
might be a hazard to workers; it is unlikely to spread to the
community; there is usually effective prophylaxis or treatment
available.
3. Group 3 biological agent: one that can cause severe human disease
and present a serious hazard to workers; it may present a risk of
spreading to the community, but there is usually effective prophylaxis
or treatment available.
4. Group 4 biological agent: one that causes severe human disease and
is a serious hazard to workers; it may present a high risk of
spreading to the community; there is usually no effective prophylaxis
or treatment available.

Additional information on SBV from Germany and Netherlands, and
relevant information from other EU members, is anticipated with
interest.

References
----------
1. Causey OR, Kemp GE, Causey CE, Lee VH: Isolations of Simbu-group
viruses in Ibadan, Nigeria 1964-69, including the new types Sango,
Shamonda, Sabo and Shuni. Ann Trop Med Parasitol. 1972; 66(3):
357-62.
2. Lee VH (1979). Isolation of viruses from field populations of
_Culicoides_ (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae) in Nigeria. J Med Entomol.
1979; 16(1): 76-9
3. Yanase T, Maeda K, Kato T, Nyuta S, et al: The resurgence of
Shamonda virus, an African Simbu group virus of the genus
_Orthobunyavirus_, in Japan. Arch Virol. 2005; 150(2): 361-9
(available at
http://www.springerlink.com/content/8H2N504NRUQRW099/fulltext.pdf/).
- Mod.AS

